{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Aw3U6AHsAVXZ7CnBmBDrLs","type":"tool_result","content":"560\t\t// TODO: Currently we assume that in a given Cacher object, its <c.triggerFunc>\n561\t\t// is aware of exactly the same trigger (at most one). Thus calling:\n562\t\t//   c.triggerFunc(<some object>)\n563\t\t// can return only 0 or 1 values.\n564\t\t// That means, that triggerValues itself may return up to 2 different values.\n565\t\tif c.triggerFunc == nil {\n566\t\t\treturn nil, false\n567\t\t}\n568\t\tresult := make([]string, 0, 2)\n569\t\tmatchValues := c.triggerFunc(event.Object)\n570\t\tif len(matchValues) > 0 {\n571\t\t\tresult = append(result, matchValues[0].Value)\n572\t\t}\n573\t\tif event.PrevObject == nil {\n574\t\t\treturn result, len(result) > 0\n575\t\t}\n576\t\tprevMatchValues := c.triggerFunc(event.PrevObject)\n577\t\tif len(prevMatchValues) > 0 {\n578\t\t\tif len(result) == 0 || result[0] != prevMatchValues[0].Value {\n579\t\t\t\tresult = append(result, prevMatchValues[0].Value)\n580\t\t\t}\n581\t\t}\n582\t\treturn result, len(result) > 0\n583\t}\n584\t\n585\tfunc (c *Cacher) processEvent(event *watchCacheEvent) {\n586\t\tif curLen := int64(len(c.incoming)); c.incomingHWM.Update(curLen) {\n587\t\t\t// Monitor if this gets backed up, and how much.\n588\t\t\tglog.V(1).Infof(\"cacher (%v): %v objects queued in incoming channel.\", c.objectType.String(), curLen)\n589\t\t}\n590\t\tc.incoming <- *event\n591\t}\n592\t\n593\tfunc (c *Cacher) dispatchEvents() {\n594\t\tfor {\n595\t\t\tselect {\n596\t\t\tcase event, ok := <-c.incoming:\n597\t\t\t\tif !ok {\n598\t\t\t\t\treturn\n599\t\t\t\t}\n600\t\t\t\tc.dispatchEvent(&event)\n601\t\t\tcase <-c.stopCh:\n602\t\t\t\treturn\n603\t\t\t}\n604\t\t}\n605\t}\n606\t\n607\tfunc (c *Cacher) dispatchEvent(event *watchCacheEvent) {\n608\t\ttriggerValues, supported := c.triggerValues(event)\n609\t\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be con